0w" width="1364" height="2048" alt="Red Saree" style="aspect-ratio:1364 / 2048" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-nVkyK eXnudJ pf-25_"/><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-cTAqQK eHolsa pf-26_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-28_">The Birth of Masterpiece </span></h2><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-29_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-31_">The handmade baluchari silk sarees got its name from a small village called Baluchur in the Murshidabad area, where the weaving of the sarees started about 200 years ago, under the rule of Murshidquali Khan, Nawab of Bengal. This rich weaving culture was introduced from Dhaka to the Baluchar village of Murshidabad, and due to its versatility, the growth of this sector took a pace over time.<br>Due to unsupportive political and economic factors, it became a dying skill as numerous weavers were forced to leave their line of work. Later, the spark was re-ignited, and people were now learning jacquard looms; the weavers made an accomplishment for working on these types of handlooms. Now, the artisans are skilled in producing authentic baluchari silk sarees that are endearing, enticing, and exquisitely enviable!
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-cTAqQK eHolsa pf-32_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-34_">Satisfactory  Baluchari Silk Saree Weaving Process</span></h2><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-35_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-37_">The <a href="https://www.indyvogue.com/blogs/indyvogue-fashion-center/history-to-know-before-you-buy-baluchari-silk-mark-sarees" target="_blank">history of Baluchari Silk Saree</a> weaving starts with the rearing of mulberry silkworms to produce raw silk. The silk yarns are extracted from the silkworm's cocoons. These are made smooth by boiling in hot water and soda. Then they are colored using an acid dye. Then the yarn is processed by stretching from both sides in opposite directions, putting some force with both palms, which makes the yarn crisper and ready for other processes, including dyeing and weaving with the Jala technique.<br>And after the dedicated craftsmanship, here comes a woven wonder: Handmade Baluchari Silk Saree.  
